# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: synthetic-biology-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BioBrick parts are used by applying engineering principles of abstraction and modularization.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] BioBrick parts form the base of the hierarchical system on which synthetic biology is based.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Device: Collection set of parts with defined function.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] In simple terms, a set of complementary BioBrick parts put together forms a device.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] System: Combination of a set of devices that performs high-level tasks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The development of standardized biological parts allows for the rapid assembly of sequences.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The ability to test individual parts and devices to be independently tested and characterized also improves the reliability of higher-order systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The first attempt to create a list of standard biological parts was in 1996, by *Rebatchouk et al*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This team introduced a cloning strategy for the assembly of short DNA fragments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] However, this early attempt was not widely recognised by the scientific research community at the time.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] In 1999, Arkin and Endy realized that the heterogeneous elements that made up a genetic circuit were lacking standards, so they proposed a list of standard biological parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] BioBricks were described and introduced by Tom Knight at MIT in 2003.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Since then, various research groups have utilized the BioBrick standard parts to engineer novel biological devices and systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BioBricks Foundation was formed in 2006 by engineers and scientists alike as a not-for-profit organization to standardize biological parts across the field.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The Foundation focuses on improving in areas of Technology, Law, Education and the Global Community as they apply to synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] BioBricks Foundation's activities include hosting SBx.0 Conferences, technical and educational programs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The SBx.0 conferences are international conferences on synthetic biology hosted across the world.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Technical programs are aimed at the production of a series of standard biological parts, and their education expansion is creating acts which help create open, standardized sources of biological parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] As an alternative to traditional biotechnology patent systems and in an effort to allow BioBricks to be utilized as an open-source community standard, the BioBricks Foundation created the BioBrick Public Agreement, which consists of a Contributor Agreement and a User Agreement.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Those who want to give a part to the community sign the Contributor Agreement, agreeing not to assert against Users Contributor-held intellectual property rights that might limit the use of the contributed materials.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Signers of the User Agreement may freely use the whole collection of parts given by contributors.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] There is no requirement for users to contribute to the community in order to use the parts, and users may assert intellectual property rights to inventions developed by using the parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The User Agreement allows users to establish invention of uses of parts, to disclose patents on parts combinations, and to freely build on the contributions of other users.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BioBrick assembly standard was introduced to overcome the lack of standardization posed by traditional molecular cloning methods.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BioBrick assembly standard is a more reliable approach for combining parts to form larger composites.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The assembly standard enables two groups of synthetic biologists in different parts of the world to re-use a BioBrick part without going through the whole cycle of design and manipulation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This means the newly designed part can be used by other teams of researchers more easily.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Besides that, when compared to the old-fashioned *ad hoc* cloning method, the assembly standard process is faster and promotes automation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BioBrick assembly standard 10 was the first assembly standard to be introduced.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Over the years, several other assembly standards, such as the Biofusion standard and Freiburg standard have been developed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Assembly standard 10 was developed by Tom Knight, and is the most widely used assembly standard.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] It involves the use of restriction enzymes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Every BioBrick part is a DNA sequence which is carried by a circular plasmid, which acts as a vector.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The vector acts as a transport system to carry the BioBrick parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The first approach towards a BioBrick standard was the introduction of standard sequences, the prefix and suffix sequences, which flank the 5′ and 3′ ends of the DNA part respectively.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] These standard sequences encode specific restriction enzyme sites.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The prefix sequence encodes *EcoRI* (E) and *Xbal* (X) sites, while the suffix sequence encodes *SpeI* (S) and *PstI* (P) sites.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The prefix and the suffix are not considered part of the BioBrick part.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] To facilitate the assembly process, the BioBrick part itself must not contain any of these restriction sites.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] During the assembly of two different parts, one of the plasmids is digested with *EcoRI* and *SpeI*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The plasmid carrying the other BioBrick part is digested with *EcoRI* and *Xbal*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This leaves both plasmids with 4 base pair (bp) overhangs at the 5′ and 3′ ends.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The *EcoRI* sites will ligate since they are complementary to each other.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The *Xbal* and *SpeI* sites will also ligate as the digestion produces compatible ends.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Now, both the DNA parts are in one plasmid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The ligation produces an 8 base pair "scar" site between the two BioBrick parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Since the scar site is a hybrid of the *Xbal* and *SpeI* sites, it is not recognized by either restriction enzyme.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The prefix and suffix sequences remain unchanged by this digestion and ligation process, which allows for subsequent assembly steps with more BioBrick parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This assembly is an idempotent process: multiple applications do not change the end product, and maintain the prefix and suffix.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Although the BioBrick standard assembly allows for the formation of functional modules, there is a limitation to this standard 10 approach.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The 8 bp scar site does not allow the creation of a fusion protein.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The scar site causes a frame shift which prevents the continuous reading of codons, which is required for the formation of fusion protein.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Tom Knight later developed the BB-2 assembly standard in 2008 to address problems with joining the scars of protein domains and that the scars consist of eight bases, which will yield an altered reading frame when joining protein domains.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The enzymes used for digestion of the initial parts are almost the same, but with modified prefixes and suffixes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BglBrick assembly standard was proposed by J.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Keasling in September 2009 as a standard very similar in concept to BioBrick, but enabling the generation of fusion proteins without altering the reading frame or introducing stop codons and while creating a relatively neutral amino acid linker scar (GlySer).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] A BglBrick part is as a DNA sequence flanked by 5′ EcoRI and BglII sites (GAATTCaaaAGATCT) and 3′ BamHI and XhoI sites (GGATCCaaaCTCGAG), and lacking in these same restriction sites internally.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The upstream part in the pairwise assembly is purified from an EcoRI/BamHI digest, and the downstream part+vector is purified from an EcoRI/BglII digest.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Pam Silver's lab created the Silver assembly standard to overcome the issue surrounding the formation of fusion protein.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This assembly standard is also known as Biofusion standard, and is an improvement of the BioBrick assembly standard 10.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Silver's standard involves deletion of one nucleotide from the *Xbal* and *SpeI* site, which shortens the scar site by 2 nucleotides, which now forms a 6 bp scar sequence.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The 6 bp sequence allows the reading frame to be maintained.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The scar sequence codes for the amino acid threonine (ACT) and arginine (AGA).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This minor improvement allows for the formation of in-frame fusion protein.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] However, arginine's being a large, charged amino acid is a disadvantage to the Biofusion assembly technique: these properties of arginine result in the destabilisation of the protein by the N-end rule.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The 2007 Freiburg iGEM team introduced a new assembly standard to overcome the disadvantages of the existing Biofusion standard technique.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The Freiburg team created a new set of prefix and suffix sequences by introducing additional restriction enzyme sites, *AgeI* and *NgoMIV* to the existing prefix and suffix respectively.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] These newly introduced restriction enzyme sites are BioBrick standard compatible.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The Freiburg standard still forms a 6 bp scar site, but the scar sequence (ACCGGC) now codes for threonine and glycine respectively.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This scar sequence results in a much more stable protein as the glycine forms a stable N-terminal, unlike the arginine, which signals for N-terminal degradation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The assembly technique proposed by the Freiburg team diminishes the limitations of the Biofusion standard.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Different methods are used when it comes to assembling BioBricks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This is because some standards require different materials and methods (use of different restriction enzymes), while others are due to preferences in protocol because some methods of assembly have higher efficiency and is user-friendly.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The 3A assembly method is the most commonly used, as its compatible with assembly Standard 10, Silver standard as well as the Freiburg standard.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This assembly method involves two BioBrick parts and a destination plasmid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The destination plasmid contains a toxic (lethal) gene, to ease the selection of a correctly assembled plasmid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The destination plasmids also have different antibiotic resistance genes than the plasmids carrying the BioBrick parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] All three plasmids are digested with an appropriate restriction enzyme and then allowed to ligate.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Only the correctly assembled part will produce a viable composite part contained in the destination plasmid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This allows a good selection as only the correctly assembled BioBrick parts survive.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The amplified insert assembly method does not depend on prefix and suffix sequences, allowing to be used in combination with a majority of assembly standards.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] It also has a higher transformation rate than 3A assembly, and it does not require the involved plasmids to have different antibiotic resistance genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This method reduces noise from uncut plasmids by amplifying a desired insert using PCR prior to digestion and treating the mixture with the restriction enzyme DpnI, which digests methylated DNA like plasmids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Eliminating the template plasmids with DpnI leaves only the insert to be amplified by PCR.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] To decrease the possibility of creating plasmids with unwanted combinations of insert and backbone, the backbone can be treated with phosphatase to prevent its religation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The Gibson scarless assembly method allows the joining of multiple BioBricks simultaneously.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] This method requires the desired sequences to have an overlap of 20 to 150 bps.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Because BioBricks do not have this overlap, this method requires PCR primers to create overhangs between adjacent BioBricks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] T5 exonuclease attacks the 5′ ends of sequences, creating single-stranded DNA in the ends of all sequences where the different components are designed to anneal.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] DNA polymerase then adds DNA parts to gaps in the anneal components, and a Taq ligase can seal the final strands.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The 4R/2M assembly method was designed to combine parts (BioBrick Assembly Standard 10 or Silver Standard) within existing plasmids (i.e. without PCR or subcloning).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The plasmids are reacted in vivo with sequence-specific DNA methyltransferases, so that each is modified and protected from one of two restriction endonucleases that are later used to linearize undesired circular ligation products.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The MIT group led by Tom Knight that developed BioBricks and International Genetically Engineered Machines (iGEM) competition are also the pioneers of The Registry of Standard Biological Parts (Registry).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Registry being one of the foundations of synthetic biology, provides web-based information and data on over 20,000 BioBrick parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Every BioBrick part has its unique identification code which makes the search for the desired BioBrick part easier (for example, BBa_J23100, a constitutive promoter).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The registry is open access, whereby anyone can submit a BioBrick part.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Most of the BioBrick submission is from students participating in the annual iGEM competition hosted every summer.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The Registry allows exchange of data and materials online which allows rapid re-use and modifications of parts by the participating community.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Professional parts registries have also been developed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] Since most of the BioBrick parts are submitted by undergraduates as part of the iGEM competition, the parts may lack important characterisation data and metadata which would be essential when it comes to designing and modelling the functional components.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] One example of a professional parts registry is the USA-based publicly funded facility, The International Open Facility Advancing Biotechnology (BIOFAB), which contains detailed descriptions of each biological part.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] It is also an open-source registry, and is available commercially.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] BIOFAB aims to catalogue high-quality BioBrick parts to accommodate the needs of professional synthetic biology community.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BioBrick Foundation (BBF) is a public-benefit organization established to promote the use of standardized BioBrick parts on a scale beyond the iGEM competition.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/biobrick] The BBF is currently working on the derivation of standard framework to promote the production high quality BioBrick parts which would be freely available to everyone.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The concept of minimal genome arose from the observations that many genes do not appear to be necessary for survival.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Therefore, if a collection of all the essential genes were put together, a minimum genome could be created artificially in a stable environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] By adding more genes, the creation of an organism of desired characteristics is possible.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] To create a new organism in this way, a scientist must determine the minimal set of genes required for metabolism and replication, which can be achieved by experimental and computational analysis of their biochemical pathways.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] A good model for a minimal genome is *Mycoplasma genitalium*, due to its very small genome size.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Most genes that are used by this organism are considered essential for survival, and from them a minimal set of 256 genes has been proposed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Once the set of essential genetic elements are known, one can proceed to define the key pathways and core-players by modeling simulations and wet lab genome engineering.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Scientifically, minimal genome projects allow the identification of the most essential genes and a reduction of genetic complexity, making engineered strains more predictable.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Industrially and agriculturally, they could be used to engineer plants to resist herbicides or harsh environments; bacteria to synthetically produce chemicals; or microbes to produce beneficial bio-products.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Proteins involved in the minimum bacterial genome tend to be substantially closer related to proteins found in archaea and eukaryotes than the average gene in the bacterial genome, indicating a substantial number of universally (or near universally) conserved proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The minimal genomes reconstructed on the basis of existing genes do not preclude simpler systems in more primitive cells, such as RNA world genomes which do not need DNA replication machinery, which are otherwise part of the minimal genome of current cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The genes which most frequently survive gene loss include those involved in DNA replication, transcription, and translation, although a number of exceptions are known.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] For example, loss can be frequently seen in subunits of the DNA polymerase holoenzyme and some DNA repair genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The majority of ribosomal proteins are retained, though some, like rpmC, can be missing.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In some cases, certain tRNA synthetases are lost.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Gene loss is also seen in genes for components in the cellular envelope, biosynthesis of biomolecules like purine, energy metabolism, and more.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Genes that are prone to gene loss without adverse effect can be excluded from minimal genomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The minimal genome corresponds to small genome sizes, as bacterial genome size correlates with the number of protein-coding genes, typically one gene per kilobase.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Mycoplasma genitalium, with a 580 kb genome and 482 protein-coding genes, is a key model for minimal genomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The smallest known genome of a free-living bacterium is 1.3 Mb with ~1100 genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] However, significantly smaller genomes are commonly observed in naturally occurring symbiotic and parasitic organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] These effects coincide with the proliferation of mobile genetic elements, pseudogenes, genome rearrangements, and chromosomal deletion.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] This is because the symbiont or parasite can outsource cellular functions to the other organism, and subsequently lose the genes meant to perform the outsourced functions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Beneficial symbionts have a greater capacity for genome reduction than parasites, as host co-adaptation allows them to lose additional genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Another important distinction between genome reduction in parasites and genome reduction in endosymbionts is that parasites lose both the gene and its associated function, whereas endosymbionts often retain the function of the lost gene since that function is taken over by the host.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The most extreme examples of genome reduction have been found in maternally transmitted endosymbionts which have experienced lengthy coevolution with their hosts and, in the process, lost a substantial amount of their cellular autonomy.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] For endosymbionts in some lineages, it is possible for the entire genome to be lost.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] For example, some mitosomes and hydrogenosomes (degenerate versions of the mitochondria known in some organisms) have experienced a total gene loss and have no remaining genes, whereas the human mitochondria still retains some of its genome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The extant genome in the human mitochondrial organelle is 16.6kb in length and contains 37 genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The mitochondrial genome can code for between 3 and 67 proteins, which suggests that the last eukaryotic common ancestor encoded a minimum of 70 genes in its genome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The smallest known mitochondrial genome is that of *Plasmodium falciparum*, with a genome size of 6kb containing three protein-coding genes and a few rRNA genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] (On the other hand, the largest known mitochondrial genome is 490kb.) Genomes nearly as small can also be found in related apicomplexans.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Conversely, the mitochondrial genomes of terrestrial plants have expanded to over 200kb with the largest one (at over 11Mb) exceeding the size of the genome of bacteria and even the simplest eukaryotes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Organelles known as plastids in plants (including chloroplasts, chromoplasts, and leucoplasts), once free-living cyanobacteria, typically retain longer genomes on the order of 100-200kb with 80-250 genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In one analysis of 15 chloroplast genomes, the analyzed chloroplasts had between 60 and 200 genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Across these chloroplasts, a total of 274 distinct protein-coding genes were identified, and only 44 of them were universally found in all sequenced chloroplast genomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Examples of organisms which have experienced genome reduction include species of *Buchnera*, *Chlamydia*, *Treponema*, *Mycoplasma*, and many others.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Comparisons of multiple sequenced genomes of endosymbionts in multiple isolates of the same species and lineage have confirmed that even long-time symbionts are still experiencing gene loss and transfer to the nucleus.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Nuclear integrants of mitochondrial or plastid DNA have sometimes been termed "numts" and "nupts" respectively.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] A number of symbionts have been discovered with genomes under 500 kb in length, the majority of them being bacterial symbionts of insects, typically from the taxa *Pseudomonadota* and *Bacteroidota*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The parasitic archaea *Nanoarchaeum equitans* has a genome 491 kb in length.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In 2002, it was found that some species of the genus *Buchnera* have a reduced genome of only 450 kb in size.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In 2021, the endosymbiont *Candidatus* *Azoamicus ciliaticola* was found to have a genome 290 kb in length.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The symbiont *Zinderia insecticola* was found to have a genome of 208 kb in 2010.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In 2006, another endosymbiont *Carsonella ruddii* was found with a reduced genome 160 kb in length encompassing 182 protein-coding genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Surprisingly, it was found that gene loss in *Carsonella* symbionts is an ongoing process.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Intermediate stages in gene loss have been observed in other reduced genomes, including the transition of some genes into pseudogenes because the host carries out the purpose of the gene.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The genome of *Candidatus* *Hodgkinia cicadicola*, a symbiont of cicadas, was found to be 144 kb.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In 2011, *Tremblaya princeps* was found to contain an intracellular endosymbiont with a genome of 139 kb, reduced to the point that even some translation genes had been lost.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] A 2013 study found two leafhopper symbionts contained highly reduced genomes: *Sulcia muelleri*, with a genome of 190 kb, and *Nasuia deltocephalinicola* with a genome of only 112 kb and 137 protein-coding genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The genomes of these two symbionts combined can only synthesize ten amino acids, in addition to some of the machinery involved in DNA replication, transcription, and translation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The genes for ATP synthesis through oxidative phosphorylation have been lost, however.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Viruses and virus-like particles have the smallest genomes in nature.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] For instance, bacteriophage MS2 consists of only 3569 nucleotides (single-stranded RNA) and encodes just four proteins, which overlap to make efficient use of the genome space.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Similarly, among eukaryotic viruses, porcine circoviruses are among the smallest.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] They encode only 2–3 open reading frames.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Viroids are circular RNA molecules which do not have any protein-coding genes at all, although the RNA molecule itself acts as a ribozyme to help enable its replication.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The genome of a viroid is between 200 and 400 nucleotides in length.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The study of minimal genomes arose as a result of a collaborative effort between National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) and two scientists: Harold Morowitz and Mark Tourtellotte.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In the 1960s, NASA was searching for extraterrestrial life forms, assuming that if they existed they may be simple creatures.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] To attract people's attention, Morowitz published about mycoplasmas and how they are the smallest and simplest self-replicating creatures.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] NASA and the two scientists decided to try to assemble a living cell from the components of mycoplasmas.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Mycoplasmas were selected as the best candidate for cell reassembly, since they are composed of a minimum set of organelles, such as a plasma membrane, ribosomes and a circular double stranded DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Morowitz' major idea was to define the entire machinery of mycoplasmas cell on the molecular level.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] He announced that an international effort would help him accomplish this main objective.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] By the 1980s, Richard Herrmann's laboratory had fully sequenced and genetically characterized the 800kb genome of *M. pneumoniae*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Despite the small size of the genome, the process took three years.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In 1995, another laboratory from Maryland the Institute for Genomic Research (TIGR) collaborated with the teams of Johns Hopkins and the University of North Carolina.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] This group chose to sequence the genome of Mycoplasma genitalium, consisting of only 580 kb genome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Finding a minimal set of essential genes was done by selective inactivation or deletions of genes and then testing the effect of each under a given set of conditions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Craig Venter institute conducted these types of experiments on *M. genitalium* and found 382 essential genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The J.Craig Venter institute later started a project to create a synthetic organism named Mycoplasma laboratorium, using the minimal set genes identified from *M. genitalium*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] As of 1999, the two organisms considered to have a near minimal genome are: *Haemophilus influenzae*, and *M. genitalium*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] A list of their orthologous proteins were compiled in hope that it would contain the proteins necessary for cell survival, as orthologous analysis determines how two organisms evolved, showing the non-essential genes accumulated in their genomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Since *H. influenza* is Gram negative and *M. genitalium* is Gram positive, and because of their long evolution, it was expected that these organisms would primarily share genes that were of universal importance.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] However, 244 detected orthologs contained no parasitism-specific proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The conclusion of this analysis was that similar biochemical functions might be performed by non-orthologous proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Even when biochemical pathways of these two organisms were mapped, several pathways were present but many were incomplete.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Proteins determined to be common between the two organisms were non-orthologous.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Much of the research focuses on the ancestral genome, and less on the minimal genome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Studies of these existing genomes have helped determine that orthologous genes found in these two species are not necessarily essential for survival, in fact non-orthologous genes were found to be more important.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Also, it was determined that proteins do not need to have the same sequence or three dimensional folds to share the same functions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Craig Venter Institute (JCVI) conducted a study to find all the essential genes of *M. genitalium* through global transposon mutagenesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] As a result, they found that 382 out of 482 protein coding genes were essential.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Genes encoding proteins of unknown function constituted 28% of the essential protein coding genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Before conducting this study, the JCVI had performed another study on the non-essential genes of *M.genitalium*, where they reported the use of transposon mutagenesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Despite identifying the non-essential genes, it is not confirmed that the products of these genes have any important biological functions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] It was only through gene essentiality studies of bacteria that JCVI was able to compose a hypothetical minimal gene set.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In JCVI's 1999 study among the two organisms, *M. genitalium* and *Mycoplasma pneumoniae* they mapped approximately 2,200 transposon insertion sites and identified 130 putative non-essential genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In their experiment they grew a set of Tn4001 transformed cells and isolated the genomic DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Amplicons were sequenced to detect the transposon insertion sites in mycoplasma genomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Genes that contained the transposon insertions were hypothetical proteins or proteins considered non-essential.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] During this process some of the disruptive genes once considered non-essential, after more analyses were found to be essential.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] This error could have been because genes were tolerant of the transposon insertions, cells contained two copies of the same gene, or gene products were supplied by more than one cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Insertion of transposon in a gene meant it was disturbed, but because they did not confirm the absence of gene products they mistook all disrupted genes as non-essential genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Some of the disrupted genes thought to be essential were isoleucyl and tyrosyl-tRNA synthetases (MG345 and MG455), DNA replication gene *dnaA* (MG469), and DNA polymerase III subunit a (MG261).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The 1999 study was later expanded, and the updated results were published in 2005.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] They improved the study by isolating and characterizing *M. genitalium* Tn4001 insertions in each colony individually, which provided more results and estimates of essential genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The key improvement in the study was isolating and characterizing individual transposon mutants.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Previously, they isolated many colonies containing a mixture of mutants.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The filter cloning approach helped in separating the mixtures of mutants.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In the 2005 study, they claim completely different sets of non-essential genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The 130 non-essential genes claimed at first were reduced to 67.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Of the remaining 63 genes, 26 genes were only disrupted in *M. pneumoniae* which means that some *M. genitalium* orthologs of non-essential *M. pneumoniae* genes were actually essential.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] They have now identified almost all of the non-essential genes in *M. genitalium*, the number of gene disruptions based on colonies analyzed plateaued and they claim a total of 100 non-essential genes out of the 482 protein coding genes in *M. genitalium*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The ultimate result of the JCVI projects came down to constructing a synthetic organism, *Mycoplasma laboratorium,* based on the 387 protein coding region and 43 structural RNA genes found in *M. genitalium*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Researchers at the JCVI in 2010 successfully created a synthetic bacterial cell that was capable of replicating itself.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The team synthesized a 1.08 million base pair chromosome of a modified *Mycoplasma mycoides*, called *Mycoplasma mycoides* JCVI-syn1.0.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The DNA was designed in a computer, synthesized, and transplanted into a cell from which the original genome had been removed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The original molecules and on-going reaction networks of the recipient cell then used the artificial DNA to generate daughter cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] These daughter cells are of synthetic origin and capable of further replication.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The first half of the project took 15 years to complete.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The team designed an accurate, digitized genome of *M. mycoides*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] A total of 1,078 cassettes were built, each 1,080 base pairs long.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] These cassettes were designed in a way that the end of each DNA cassette overlapped by 80 base pairs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The whole assembled genome was transplanted in yeast cells and grown as yeast artificial chromosome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] After further refinement and gene reduction, JCVI-syn3.0 was constructed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The number of essential genes is different for each organism.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] For instance, the genome of *E. coli* can be reduced by about 30%, demonstrating that this species can live with much fewer genes than the genome contains in the wild.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Each organism has a different number of essential genes, depending on which strain (or individual) is tested.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In addition, the number depends on the conditions under which an organism is tested.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] In several bacteria (or other microbes such as yeast) all or most genes have been deleted individually to determine which genes are "essential" for survival.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] Such tests are usually carried out on rich media which contain all nutrients.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] However, if all nutrients are provided, genes required for the synthesis of nutrients are not "essential".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] When cells are grown on minimal media, many more genes are essential as they may be needed to synthesize such nutrients (e.g. vitamins).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The numbers provided in the following table typically have been collected using rich media.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The number of essential genes were collected from the Database of Essential Genes (DEG), except for *B. subtilis*, where the data comes from Genome News Network The organisms listed in this table have been systematically tested for essential genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/minimal-genome] The following table contains a list of minimal genome projects, finding the number of essential genes for various organisms, (including the various techniques used).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] A **protocell** (or **protobiont**) is a self-organized, membrane-bound or membraneless compartment that concentrates biomolecules, proposed as a rudimentary precursor to cells during the origin of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] It is a minimal unit that can undergo Darwinian evolution.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The term "protocell" is used interchangeably with other terms such as "artificial cell", "minimal cell", "synthetic cell" to describe similar things.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] A central question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and how their progeny could diversify, thus enabling the accumulation of novel biological emergences over time (i.e. biological evolution).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Although a functional protocell that evolves has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting, the goal to understand the process appears possible.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Compartmentalization was important in the origin of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Membranes form enclosed compartments that are separate from the external environment, thus providing the cell with functionally specialized aqueous spaces.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] As the lipid bilayer of membranes is impermeable to most hydrophilic molecules (dissolved by water), modern cells have membrane transport-systems that achieve nutrient uptake as well as the export of waste.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Prior to the development of these molecular assemblies, protocells likely employed vesicle dynamics that are relevant to cellular functions, such as membrane trafficking and self-reproduction, using amphiphilic molecules.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] On the primitive Earth, numerous chemical reactions of organic compounds produced the ingredients of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Of these substances, amphiphilic molecules might be the first player in the evolution from molecular assembly to cellular life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Vesicle dynamics could progress towards protocells with the development of self-replication coupled with early metabolism.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] It is possible that protocells might have had a primitive metabolic system (Wood-Ljungdahl pathway) at alkaline hydrothermal vents or other geological environments like impact crater lakes from meteorites, which are known to be composed of elements found in the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Another conceptual model of a protocell relates to the term "chemoton" (short for 'chemical automaton') which refers to the fundamental unit of life introduced by Hungarian theoretical biologist Tibor Gánti.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] It is the oldest known computational abstract of a protocell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Gánti conceived the basic idea in 1952 and formulated the concept in 1971 in his book *The Principles of Life* (originally written in Hungarian, and translated to English only in 2003).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] He surmised the chemoton as the original ancestor of all organisms, or the last universal common ancestor.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The basic assumption of the chemoton model is that life should fundamentally and essentially have three properties: metabolism, self-replication, and a bilipid membrane.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The metabolic and replication functions together form an autocatalytic subsystem necessary for the basic functions of life, and a membrane encloses this subsystem to separate it from the surrounding environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Therefore, any system having such properties may be regarded as alive, and will contain self-sustaining cellular information that is subject to natural selection.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Some consider this model a significant contribution to origin of life as it provides a philosophy of evolutionary units.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The second law of thermodynamics requires that the universe becomes increasingly disordered (entropy), yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate life processes from non-living matter.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This fundamental necessity is underpinned by the universality of the cell membrane which is the only cellular structure found in all organisms on Earth.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In the aqueous environment in which all known cells function, a non-aqueous barrier is required to surround a cell and separate it from its surroundings.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This non-aqueous membrane establishes a barrier to free diffusion, allowing for regulation of the internal environment within the barrier.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The necessity of thermodynamically isolating a subsystem is an irreducible condition of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In modern biology, such isolation is ordinarily accomplished by amphiphilic bilayers of a thickness of around 10−8 meters.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Szostak have demonstrated that simple physicochemical properties of elementary protocells can give rise to simpler conceptual analogues of essential cellular behaviors, including primitive forms of Darwinian competition and energy storage.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Such cooperative interactions between the membrane and encapsulated contents could greatly simplify the transition from replicating molecules to true cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for the evolution of cross-linked fatty acids and even the phospholipids of today.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This micro-encapsulation allowed for metabolism within the membrane, exchange of small molecules and prevention of passage of large substances across it.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The main advantages of encapsulation include increased solubility of the cargo and creating energy in the form of chemical gradients.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Energy is thus often said to be stored by cells in molecular structures such as carbohydrates (including sugars), lipids, and proteins, which release energy when chemically combined with oxygen during cellular respiration.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] When phospholipids or simple lipids like fatty acids are placed in water, the molecules spontaneously arrange such that the hydrophobic tails are shielded from the water, resulting in the formation of membrane structures such as bilayers, vesicles, and micelles.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In modern cells, vesicles are involved in metabolism, transport, buoyancy control, and enzyme storage.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] They can also act as natural chemical reaction chambers.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] A typical vesicle or micelle in aqueous solution forms an aggregate with the hydrophilic "head" regions in contact with surrounding solvent, sequestering the hydrophobic single-tail regions in the micelle center.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This phase is caused by the packing behavior of single-tail lipids in a bilayer.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] However, in a prebiotic context, electrostatic interactions induced by short, positively charged, hydrophobic peptides containing seven amino acids in length or fewer, can attach RNA to a vesicle membrane, the basic cell membrane.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Rather than being made up of phospholipids, early membranes may have formed from monolayers or bilayers of simple fatty acids, which may have formed more readily in a prebiotic environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Fatty acids have been synthesized in laboratories under a variety of prebiotic conditions and have been found on meteorites, suggesting their natural synthesis in nature.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Oleic acid vesicles represent good models of membrane protocells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] (2021) suggested that the formation of model protocells from multilamellar lipid reservoirs starting from mixed amphiphiles is a plausible scenario for the emergence of the first cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] (2022) suggested that plausible prebiotic production of fatty acids — leading to the development of early protocell membranes — is enriched on metal-rich mineral surfaces, possibly from impact craters, increasing the prebiotic environmental mass of lipids by 102 times.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] They evaluated three different possible synthesis pathways of fatty acids in the Hadean, and found that these metal surfaces could produce 1011 - 1015 kg of 6-18 carbon fatty acids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Of these products, the 8-18C fatty acids are compatible with membrane formation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] They also proposed that alternative amphiphiles like alcohols are co-synthesized with fatty acid, and can help improve membrane stability.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] However, despite this production, the authors stated that net fatty acid synthesis would not yield sufficient concentrations for spontaneous membrane formation without significant evaporation of Earth's aqueous environments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] (2024) showed that cysteine can generate membrane vesicles characteristic of protocells by spontaneously reacting with two short-chain thioesters to form diacyl lipids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] That same year, Pulletikurti et al. showed a potential mechanism for the transition from fatty-acid-based to phospholipid vesicles using cyclic-phospholipids formed from fatty acids and glycerol.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Also that year, while replicating the Miller-Urey experiment, Jenewein et al. found that silica in the presence of water induces the formation of biomorphic protocells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] For cellular organisms, the transport of specific molecules across compartmentalizing membrane barriers is essential in order to exchange content with their environment and with other individuals.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] For example, content exchange between individuals enables the exchange of genes between individuals (horizontal gene transfer), an important factor in the evolution of cellular life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] While modern cells can rely on complicated protein machineries to catalyze these crucial processes, protocells must have accomplished this using more simple mechanisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Protocells composed of fatty acids would have been able to easily exchange small molecules and ions with their environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Modern phospholipid bilayer cell membranes exhibit low permeability, but contain complex molecular assemblies which both actively and passively transport relevant molecules across the membrane in a highly specific manner.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In the absence of these complex assemblies, simple fatty acid based protocell membranes would be more permeable and allow for greater non-specific transport across membranes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Molecules that would be highly permeable across protocell membranes include nucleoside monophosphate (NMP), nucleoside diphosphate (NDP), and nucleoside triphosphate (NTP), and may withstand millimolar concentrations of Mg2+.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Osmotic pressure can also play a significant role regarding this passive membrane transport.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Environmental effects have been suggested to trigger conditions under which a transport of larger molecules, such as DNA and RNA, across the membranes of protocells is possible.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] For example, it has been proposed that electroporation resulting from lightning strikes could enable such transport.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Electroporation is the rapid increase in bilayer permeability induced by the application of a large artificial electric field across the membrane.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] During electroporation, the lipid molecules in the membrane shift position, opening up a pore (hole) that acts as a conductive pathway through which hydrophobic molecules like nucleic acids can pass the lipid bilayer.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] A similar transfer of content across protocells and with the surrounding solution can be caused by freezing and subsequent thawing.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This could, for instance, occur in an environment in which day and night cycles cause recurrent freezing.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Laboratory experiments have shown that such conditions allow an exchange of genetic information between populations of protocells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This can be explained by the fact that membranes are highly permeable at temperatures slightly below their phase transition temperature.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] If this point is reached during the freeze-thaw cycle, even large and highly charged molecules can temporarily pass the protocell membrane.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Some molecules or particles are too large or too hydrophilic to pass through a lipid bilayer even under these conditions, but can be moved across the membrane through fusion or budding of vesicles, events which have also been observed for freeze-thaw cycles.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This may eventually have led to mechanisms that facilitate movement of molecules to the inside of the protocell (endocytosis) or to release its contents into the extracellular space (exocytosis).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Such coacervate‑like droplets create localized microenvironments that facilitate molecular crowding and selective enrichment of reactants, potentially lowering barriers to primitive catalysis and reaction networks important for early evolution.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The concept of condensate‑based protocells extends early coacervation theories and finds support in modern work showing how phase‑separated droplets can act as compartmentalized reaction centers for nucleic acids or peptides.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Such optically programmable crosslinks within condensates suggest mechanisms by which phase‑separated protocell analogues could persist or evolve under prebiotic conditions, offering a potential pathway for stabilizing early biochemical reaction compartments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] It has been proposed that life began in hydrothermal vents in the deep sea, but a 2012 study suggests that hot springs have the ideal characteristics for the origin of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The conclusion is based mainly on the chemistry of modern cells, where the cytoplasm is rich in potassium, zinc, manganese, and phosphate ions, not widespread in marine environments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Such conditions, the researchers argue, are found only where hot hydrothermal fluid brings the ions to the surface—places such as geysers, mud pots, fumaroles and other geothermal features.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Within these fuming and bubbling basins, water laden with zinc and manganese ions could have collected, cooled and condensed in shallow pools.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] However, a recent discovery of alkaline hydrothermal vents with an ionic concentration of sodium lower than in seawater suggests that high concentrations of potassium can be found at marine environments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] A study in the 1990s showed that montmorillonite clay can help create RNA chains of as many as 50 nucleotides joined together spontaneously into a single RNA molecule.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Later, in 2002, it was discovered that by adding montmorillonite to a solution of fatty acid micelles (lipid spheres), the clay sped up the rate of vesicle formation 100-fold.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Some minerals can catalyze the stepwise formation of hydrocarbon tails of fatty acids from hydrogen and carbon monoxide gases—gases that may have been released from hydrothermal vents or geysers.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Simple amphiphilic compounds in seawater do not assemble into vesicles because of the high concentration of ionic solutes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Research has shown that vesicles can be bound and stabilized by prebiotic amino acids even while in the presence of salt ions and magnesium ions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In hot spring conditions, self-assembly of vesicles occurs, which have a lower concentration of ionic solutes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Scientists oligomerized RNA in alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions in the laboratory.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Although they were estimated to be 4 units in length, it implies RNA polymers possibly were synthesized at such environments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Experimental research at hot springs gave higher yields of RNA-like polymers than in the laboratory.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The polymers were encapsulated in fatty acid vesicles when rehydrated, further supporting the hot spring hypothesis of abiogenesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] These wet-dry cycles also improved vesicle stability and binding.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] UV exposure has also been shown to promote the synthesis of stable biomolecules like nucleotides.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In the origin of chemiosmosis, if early cells originated at alkaline hydrothermal vents, proton gradients can be maintained by the acidic ocean and alkaline water from white smokers while an inorganic membranous structure is in a rock cavity.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Because of the "water problem", a primitive ATP synthase and other biomolecules would go through hydrolysis due to the absence of wet-dry cycles at hydrothermal vents, unlike at terrestrial pools.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Other researchers propose hydrothermal pore systems coated in mineral gels at deep sea hydrothermal vents to an alternative compartment of membranous structures, promote biochemical reactions of biopolymers, and could solve the "water problem".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] David Deamer and Bruce Damer argue that biomolecules would become trapped within these pore systems upon polymerization and would not undergo combinatorial selection.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Catalytic FeS and NiS walls at alkaline hydrothermal vents has also been suggested to have promoted polymerization.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] However, Jackson (2016) evaluates how the pH gradient between alkaline hydrothermal vents and acidic Hadean seawater might influence prebiotic synthesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Three main criticisms emerge from this evaluation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Firstly, the maintenance and stability of membranes positioned suitably between turbulent pH gradients seemed implausible.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] They claim that the proposition of CaCO3 and Mg(OH)2 precipitates interacting with fluid mixing in subsurface pores do not produce satisfactory environments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Secondly, they suggest that the molecular assemblies required to utilize key energetic gradients available at hydrothermal systems were too complex to have been relevant at the origin of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Lastly, they argue that even if a molecular assembly could have harvested available hydrothermal energy, those assemblies would have been too large to operate within the proposed membrane thicknesses accepted by proponents of the hydrothermal vent hypothesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This emergence, however, is essential to the niche differentiation of life, allowing for the diversification of habitats and energetic strategies.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] It has been considered by other researchers that life originating in hydrothermal volcanic ponds exposed to UV radiation, zinc sulfide photocatalysis, and occurrence of continuous wet-dry cycling would not resemble modern biochemistry.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Maximal ATP synthesis is shown to occur at high water activity and low ion concentrations.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Despite this, hydrothermal vents are still considered to be a feasible environment as some shallow hydrothermal vents emit freshwater and the concentration of divalent cations in Hadean oceans were likely lower than in modern oceans.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Nick Lane and coauthors state that "alkaline hydrothermal systems tend to precipitate Ca2+ and Mg2+ ions as aragonite and brucite, so their concentrations are typically much lower than mean ocean values.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Modelling work in relation to Hadean systems indicates that hydrothermal concentrations of Ca2+ and Mg2+ would likely have been <1 mM, which is in the range that enhanced phosphorylation here.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Other conditions considered here, including salinity and high pressure, would have only limited effects on ATP synthesis in submarine hydrothermal systems (which typically have pressures in the range of 100 to 300 Bars).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Alkaline hydrothermal systems might also have generated Fe3+ in situ for ADP phosphorylation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Thermodynamic modelling shows that the mixing of alkaline hydrothermal fluids with seawater in submarine systems can promote continuous cycling between ferrous and ferric iron, potentially forming soluble hydrous ferric chlorides, which our experiments show have the same effect as ferric sulphate".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Another group suggests that primitive cells might have formed inside inorganic clay microcompartments, which can provide an ideal container for the synthesis and compartmentalization of complex organic molecules.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Clay-armored *bubbles* form naturally when particles of montmorillonite clay collect on the outer surface of air bubbles under water.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This creates a semi permeable vesicle from materials that are readily available in the environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The authors remark that montmorillonite is known to serve as a chemical catalyst, encouraging lipids to form membranes and single nucleotides to join into strands of RNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Primitive reproduction can be envisioned when the clay bubbles burst, releasing the lipid membrane-bound product into the surrounding medium.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Another way to form primitive compartments that may lead to the formation of a protocell is polyesters membraneless structures that have the ability to host biochemicals (proteins and RNA) and/or scaffold the assemblies of lipids around them.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] While these droplets are leaky towards genetic materials, this leakiness could have facilitated the progenote hypothesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Researchers have also proposed early encapsulation in aqueous phase-separated droplets called coacervates.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] These droplets are driven by the accumulation of macromolecules, producing a distinct dense phase liquid droplet within a more dilute liquid medium.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] These droplets can propagate, retaining their internal composition, through shear forces and turbulence in the medium, and could have acted as a means of replicating encapsulation for an early protocell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] However, replication was highly disordered and droplet fusion is common, calling into question coacervates true potential for distinct compartmentalization leading to competition and early Darwinian-selection.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Eigen *et al.*. and Woese proposed that the genomes of early protocells were composed of single-stranded RNA, and that individual genes corresponded to separate RNA segments, rather than being linked end-to-end as in present-day DNA genomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] A protocell that was haploid (one copy of each RNA gene) would be vulnerable to damage, since a single lesion in any RNA segment would be potentially lethal to the protocell (e.g. by blocking replication or inhibiting the function of an essential gene).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Vulnerability to damage could be reduced by maintaining two or more copies of each RNA segment in each protocell, i.e. by maintaining diploidy or polyploidy.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Genome redundancy would allow a damaged RNA segment to be replaced by an additional replication of its homolog.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] For such a simple organism, the proportion of available resources tied up in the genetic material would be a large fraction of the total resource budget.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Under limited resource conditions, the protocell reproductive rate would likely be inversely related to ploidy number, and the protocell's fitness would be reduced by the costs of redundancy.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Consequently, coping with damaged RNA genes while minimizing the costs of redundancy would likely have been a fundamental problem for early protocells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] A cost-benefit analysis was carried out in which the costs of maintaining redundancy were balanced against the costs of genome damage.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This analysis led to the conclusion that, under a wide range of circumstances, the selected strategy would be for each protocell to be haploid, but to periodically fuse with another haploid protocell to form a transient diploid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The retention of the haploid state maximizes the growth rate.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The periodic fusions permit mutual reactivation of otherwise lethally damaged protocells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] If at least one damage-free copy of each RNA gene is present in the transient diploid, viable progeny can be formed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] For two, rather than one, viable daughter cells to be produced would require an extra replication of the intact RNA gene homologous to any RNA gene that had been damaged prior to the division of the fused protocell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The cycle of haploid reproduction, with occasional fusion to a transient diploid state, followed by splitting to the haploid state, can be considered to be the sexual cycle in its most primitive form.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In the absence of this sexual cycle, haploid protocells with damage in an essential RNA gene would simply die.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This model for the early sexual cycle is hypothetical, but it is very similar to the known sexual behavior of the segmented RNA viruses, which are among the simplest organisms known.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The influenza virus, whose genome consists of 8 physically separated single-stranded RNA segments, is an example of this type of virus.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In segmented RNA viruses, "mating" can occur when a host cell is infected by at least two virus particles.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] If these viruses each contain an RNA segment with a lethal damage, multiple infection can lead to reactivation providing that at least one undamaged copy of each virus gene is present in the infected cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This phenomenon is known as "multiplicity reactivation".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Multiplicity reactivation has been reported to occur in influenza virus infections after induction of RNA damage by UV-irradiation, and ionizing radiation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Starting with a technique commonly used to deposit molecules on a solid surface, Langmuir–Blodgett deposition, scientists are able to assemble phospholipid membranes of arbitrary complexity layer by layer.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] These artificial phospholipid membranes support functional insertion both of purified and of *in situ* expressed membrane proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The technique could help astrobiologists understand how the first living cells originated.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Jeewanu protocells are synthetic chemical particles that possess cell-like structure and seem to have some functional living properties.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] First synthesized in 1963 from simple minerals and basic organics while exposed to sunlight, it is still reported to have some metabolic capabilities, the presence of semipermeable membrane, amino acids, phospholipids, carbohydrates and RNA-like molecules.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The nature and properties of the Jeewanu remains to be clarified.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In a similar synthesis experiment a frozen mixture of water, methanol, ammonia and carbon monoxide was exposed to ultraviolet (UV) radiation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] This combination yielded large amounts of organic material that self-organised to form globules or vesicles when immersed in water.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The investigating scientist considered these globules to resemble cell membranes that enclose and concentrate the chemistry of life, separating their interior from the outside world.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The globules were between 10 and 40 micrometres (0.00039 and 0.00157 in), or about the size of red blood cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Remarkably, the globules fluoresced, or glowed, when exposed to UV light.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Absorbing UV and converting it into visible light in this way was considered one possible way of providing energy to a primitive cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] If such globules played a role in the origin of life, the fluorescence could have been a precursor to primitive photosynthesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Such fluorescence also provides the benefit of acting as a sunscreen, diffusing any damage that otherwise would be inflicted by UV radiation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Such a protective function would have been vital for life on the early Earth, since the ozone layer, which blocks out the sun's most destructive UV rays, did not form until after photosynthetic life began to produce oxygen.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The synthesis of three kinds of "jeewanu" have been reported; two of them were organic, and the other was inorganic.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Other similar inorganic structures have also been produced.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Kalinenko) referred to them as "bio-like structures" and "artificial cells".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Formed in distilled water (as well as on agar gel) under the influence of an electric field, they lack protein, amino acids, purine or pyrimidine bases, and certain enzyme activities.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] According to NASA researchers, "presently known scientific principles of biology and biochemistry cannot account for living inorganic units" and "the postulated existence of these living units has not been proved".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In March 2014, NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory demonstrated a unique way to study the origins of life: fuel cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Fuel cells are similar to biological cells in that electrons are also transferred to and from molecules.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] In both cases, this results in electricity and power.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The study of fuel cells suggest that an important factor in protocell development was that the Earth provides electrical energy at the seafloor.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] "This energy could have kick-started life and could have sustained life after it arose.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Protocell research has created controversy and opposing opinions, including criticism of vague definitions of "artificial life".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] The creation of a basic unit of life is the most pressing ethical concern, although the most widespread worry about protocells is their potential threat to human health and the environment through uncontrolled replication.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Additionally, postulation into the conditions for protocellular origins of life on Earth remain debated.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/protocell] Scientists in the field emphasize the importance of further hypothesis based experimentation over theoretical conjecture to more concretely constrain the prebiotic plausibility of different protocell morphologies, geologic conditions, and synthetic schemes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The **Registry of Standard Biological Parts** is a collection of genetic parts that are used in the assembly of systems and devices in synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The registry was founded in 2003 at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The registry, as of 2018, contains over 20,000 parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] Recipients of the genetic parts include academic labs, established scientists, and student teams participating in the iGEM Foundation's annual synthetic biology competition.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The Registry of Standard Biological Parts conforms to the BioBrick standard, a standard for interchangeable genetic parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] BioBrick was developed by a nonprofit composed of researchers from MIT, Harvard, and UCSF.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The registry offers genetic parts with the expectation that recipients will contribute data and new parts to improve the resource.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The registry records and indexes biological parts and offers services including the synthesis and assembly of biological parts, systems, and devices.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The registry offers many types of biological parts, including DNA, plasmids, plasmid backbones, primers, promoters, protein coding sequences, protein domains, ribosomal binding sites, terminators, translational units, riboregulators, and composite parts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] It also includes devices such as protein generators, reporters, inverters, receptors, senders, and measurement devices.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] A key idea that motivated the development of the Registry was to develop an abstraction hierarchy implemented through the parts categorization system.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/registry-of-standard-biological-parts] The registry has previously received external funding through grants from the National Science Foundation, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, and the National Institutes of Health.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It includes designing and constructing biological modules, biological systems, and biological machines, or re-designing existing biological systems for useful purposes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Additionally, it is the branch of science that focuses on the new abilities of engineering into existing organisms to redesign them for useful purposes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In order to produce predictable and robust systems with novel functionalities that do not already exist in nature, it is also necessary to apply the engineering paradigm of systems design to biological systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] According to the European Commission, this possibly involves a molecular assembler based on biomolecular systems such as the ribosome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biology is a field whose scope is expanding in terms of systems integration, engineered organisms, and practical findings.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Engineers view biology as *technology* (in other words, a given system includes *biotechnology* or its *biological engineering*).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Researchers and companies working in synthetic biology are using nature's power to solve issues in agriculture, manufacturing, and medicine.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Due to more powerful genetic engineering capabilities and decreased DNA synthesis and sequencing costs, the field of synthetic biology is rapidly growing.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In 2016, more than 350 companies across 40 countries were actively engaged in synthetic biology applications; all these companies had an estimated net worth of $3.9 billion in the global market.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biology currently has no generally accepted definition.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It is the science of emerging genetic and physical engineering to produce new (and, therefore, synthetic) life forms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] To develop organisms with novel or enhanced characteristics, this emerging field of study combines biology, engineering, and related disciplines' knowledge and techniques to design chemically synthesized DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Biomolecular engineering includes approaches that aim to create a toolkit of functional units that can be introduced to present new technological functions in living cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Genetic engineering includes approaches to construct synthetic chromosomes or minimal organisms like *Mycoplasma laboratorium*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Biomolecular design refers to the general idea of de novo design and additive combination of biomolecular components.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Each of these approaches shares a similar task: to develop a more synthetic entity at a higher level of complexity by inventively manipulating a simpler part at the preceding level.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Optimizing these exogenous pathways in unnatural systems takes iterative fine-tuning of the individual biomolecular components to select the highest concentrations of the desired product.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] On the other hand, "re-writers" are synthetic biologists interested in testing the irreducibility of biological systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Due to the complexity of natural biological systems, it would be simpler to rebuild the natural systems of interest from the ground up; to provide engineered surrogates that are easier to comprehend, control and manipulate.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Re-writers draw inspiration from refactoring, a process sometimes used to improve computer software.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Bioengineering, synthetic genomics, protocell synthetic biology, unconventional molecular biology, and in silico techniques are the five categories of synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It is necessary to review the distinctions and analogies between the categories of synthetic biology for its social and ethical assessment, to distinguish between issues affecting the whole field and particular to a specific one.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The subfield of bioengineering concentrates on creating novel metabolic and regulatory pathways, and is currently the one that likely draws the attention of most researchers and funding.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It is primarily motivated by the desire to establish biotechnology as a legitimate engineering discipline.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] When referring to this area of synthetic biology, the word "bioengineering" should not be confused with "traditional genetic engineering", which involves introducing a single transgene into the intended organism.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Bioengineers adapted synthetic biology to provide a substantially more integrated perspective on how to alter organisms or metabolic systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] A typical example of single-gene genetic engineering is the insertion of the human insulin gene into bacteria to create transgenic proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The creation of whole new signalling pathways, containing numerous genes and regulatory components (such as an oscillator circuit to initiate the periodic production of green fluorescent protein (GFP) in mammalian cells), is known as bioengineering as part of synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] By utilising simplified and abstracted metabolic and regulatory modules as well as other standardized parts that may be freely combined to create new pathways or creatures, bioengineering aims to create innovative biological systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In addition to creating infinite opportunities for novel applications, this strategy is anticipated to make bioengineering more predictable and controllable than traditional biotechnology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The formation of animals with a chemically manufactured (minimal) genome is another facet of synthetic biology that is highlighted by synthetic genomics.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This area of synthetic biology has been made possible by ongoing advancements in DNA synthesis technology, which now makes it feasible to produce DNA molecules with thousands of base pairs at a reasonable cost.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The goal is to combine these molecules into complete genomes and transplant them into living cells, replacing the host cell's genome and reprogramming its metabolism to perform different functions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Scientists have previously demonstrated the potential of this approach by creating infectious viruses by synthesising the genomes of multiple viruses.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] These significant advances in science and technology triggered the initial public concerns concerning the risks associated with this technology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] A simple genome might also work as a "chassis genome" that could be enlarged quickly by gene inclusion created for particular tasks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Such "chassis creatures" would be more suited for the insertion of new functions than wild organisms since they would have fewer biological pathways that could potentially conflict with the new functionalities in addition to having specific insertion sites.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic genomics strives to create creatures with novel "architectures," much like the bioengineering method.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It adopts an integrative or holistic perspective of the organism.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In this case, the objective is the creation of chassis genomes based on necessary genes and other required DNA sequences rather than the design of metabolic or regulatory pathways based on abstract criteria.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The in vitro generation of synthetic cells is the protocell branch of synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Lipid vesicles, which have all the necessary components to function as a complete system, can be used to create these artificial cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In the end, these synthetic cells should meet the requirements for being deemed alive, namely the capacity for self-replication, self-maintenance, and evolution.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The protocell technique has this as its end aim, however there are other intermediary steps that fall short of meeting all the criteria for a living cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In order to carry out a specific function, these lipid vesicles contain cell extracts or more specific sets of biological macromolecules and complex structures, such as enzymes, nucleic acids, or ribosomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] For instance, liposomes may carry out particular polymerase chain reactions or synthesise a particular protein.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Innovations in synthetic biology have led to the development of organelle-like scaffolds using phase-separated biomolecular condensates to compartmentalize cellular processes in Escherichia coli, such as RNA-based TEARS.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] These membraneless organelles can be engineered to scaffold metabolic pathways, or enabling protein purification with no traditional external chromatography materials by a workflow termed PandaPure.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biologists in this field view their work as basic study into the conditions necessary for life to exist and its origin more than in any of the other techniques.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The protocell technique, however, also lends itself well to applications; similar to other synthetic biology byproducts, protocells could be employed for the manufacture of biopolymers and medicines.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The objective of the "unnatural molecular biology" strategy is to create new varieties of life that are based on a different kind of molecular biology, such as new types of nucleic acids or a new genetic code.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The creation of new types of nucleotides that can be built into unique nucleic acids could be accomplished by changing certain DNA or RNA constituents, such as the bases or the backbone sugars.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The normal genetic code is being altered by inserting quadruplet codons or changing some codons to encode new amino acids, which would subsequently permit the use of non-natural amino acids with unique features in protein production.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It is a scientific and technological problem to adjust the enzymatic machinery of the cell for both approaches.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] A new sort of life would be formed by organisms with a genome built on synthetic nucleic acids or on a totally new coding system for synthetic amino acids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This new style of life would have some benefits but also some new dangers.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] On release into the environment, there would be no horizontal gene transfer or outcrossing of genes with natural species.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Furthermore, these kinds of synthetic organisms might be created to require non-natural materials for protein or nucleic acid synthesis, rendering them unable to thrive in the wild if they accidentally escaped.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biology *in silico* and the various strategies are interconnected.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The development of complex designs, whether they are metabolic pathways, fundamental cellular processes, or chassis genomes, is one of the major difficulties faced by the four synthetic-biology methods outlined above.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Because of this, synthetic biology has a robust in silico branch, similar to systems biology, that aims to create computational models for the design of common biological components or synthetic circuits, which are essentially simulations of synthetic organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The practical application of simulations and models through bioengineering or other fields of synthetic biology is the long-term goal of in silico synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Many of the computational simulations of synthetic organisms up to this point possess little to no direct analogy to living things.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Due to this, in silico synthetic biology is regarded as a separate group in this article.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It is sensible to integrate the five areas under the umbrella of synthetic biology as one unified area of study.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Even though they focus on various facets of life, such as metabolic regulation, essential elements, or biochemical makeup, these five strategies all work toward the same end: creating new types of living organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Additionally, the varied methodologies begin with numerous methodological approaches, which leads to the diversity of synthetic biology approaches.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biology is an interdisciplinary field that draws from and is inspired by many different scientific disciplines, not one single field or technique.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biologists all have the same underlying objective of designing and producing new forms of life, despite the fact that they may employ various methodologies, techniques, and research instruments.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Any evaluation of synthetic biology, whether it examines ethical, legal, or safety considerations, must take into account the fact that while some questions, risks, and issues are unique to each technique, in other circumstances, synthetic biology as a whole must be taken into consideration.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biology has traditionally been divided into four different engineering approaches: top down, parallel, orthogonal and bottom up.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] To replicate emergent behaviours from natural biology and build artificial life, unnatural chemicals are used.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The other looks for interchangeable components from biological systems to put together and create systems that do not work naturally.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In either case, a synthetic objective compels researchers to venture into new area in order to engage and resolve issues that cannot be readily resolved by analysis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Due to this, new paradigms are driven to arise in ways that analysis cannot easily do.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In addition to devices that oscillate, creep, and play tic-tac-toe, synthetic biology has produced diagnostic instruments that enhance the treatment of patients with infectious diseases.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It involves using metabolic and genetic engineering techniques to impart new functions to living cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] By comparing universal genes and eliminating non-essential ones to create a basic genome, this method seeks to lessen the complexity of existing cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] These initiatives are founded on the hypothesis of a single genesis for cellular life, the so-called Last Universal Common Ancestor, which supports the presence of a universal minimal genome that gave rise to all living things.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Recent studies, however, raise the possibility that the eukaryotic and prokaryotic cells that make up the tree of life may have evolved from a group of primordial cells rather than from a single cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] As a result, even while the Holy Grail-like pursuit of the "minimum genome" has grown elusive, cutting out a number of non-essential functions impairs an organism's fitness and leads to "fragile" genomes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This approach involves creating new biological systems in vitro by bringing together 'non-living' biomolecular components, often with the aim of constructing an artificial cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Reproduction, replication, and assembly are three crucial self-organizational principles that are taken into account in order to accomplish this.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The study of protocells exists along with other in vitro synthetic biology initiatives that seek to produce minimal cells, metabolic pathways, or "never-born proteins" as well as to mimic physiological functions including cell division and growth.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Recently a cell-free system capable of self-sustaining using CO2 was engineered by bottom-up integrating metabolism with gene expression.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Parallel engineering is also known as bioengineering.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The basic genetic code is the foundation for parallel engineering research, which uses conventional biomolecules like nucleic acids and the 20 amino acids to construct biological systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] For a variety of applications in biocomputing, bioenergy, biofuels, bioremediation, optogenetics, and medicine, it involves the standardisation of DNA components, engineering of switches, biosensors, genetic circuits, logic gates, and cellular communication operators.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] For directing the expression of two or more genes and/or proteins, the majority of these applications often rely on the use of one or more vectors (or plasmids).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Small, circular, double-strand DNA units known as plasmids, which are primarily found in prokaryotic but can also occasionally be detected in eukaryotic cells, may replicate autonomously of chromosomal DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It is also known as perpendicular engineering.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This strategy, also referred to as "chemical synthetic biology," principally seeks to alter or enlarge the genetic codes of living systems utilising artificial DNA bases and/or amino acids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This subfield is also connected to xenobiology, a newly developed field that combines systems chemistry, synthetic biology, exobiology, and research into the origins of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In recent decades, researchers have created compounds that are structurally similar to the DNA canonical bases to see if those "alien" or xeno (XNA) molecules may be employed as genetic information carriers.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Similar to this, noncanonical moieties have taken the place of the DNA sugar (deoxyribose).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In order to express information other than the 20 conventional amino acids of proteins, the genetic code can be altered or enlarged.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] One method involves incorporating a specified unnatural, noncanonical, or xeno amino acid (XAA) into one or more proteins at one or more precise places using orthogonal enzymes and a transfer RNA adaptor from an other organism.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Several novel enabling technologies were critical to the success of synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Concepts include standardization of biological parts and hierarchical abstraction to permit using those parts in synthetic systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] DNA serves as the guide for how biological processes should function, like the score to a complex symphony of life.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Our ability to comprehend and design biological systems has undergone significant modifications as a result of developments in the previous few decades in both reading (sequencing) and writing (synthesis) DNA sequences.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] These developments have produced ground-breaking techniques for designing, assembling, and modifying DNA-encoded genes, materials, circuits, and metabolic pathways, enabling an ever-increasing amount of control over biological systems and even entire organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Basic technologies include reading and writing DNA (sequencing and fabrication).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Measurements under multiple conditions are needed for accurate modeling and computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Driven by dramatic decreases in costs of oligonucleotide ("oligos") synthesis and the advent of PCR, the sizes of DNA constructions from oligos have increased to the genomic level.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In 2000, researchers reported synthesis of the 9.6 kbp (kilo bp) Hepatitis C virus genome from chemically synthesized 60 to 80-mers.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In 2002, researchers at Stony Brook University succeeded in synthesizing the 7741 bp poliovirus genome from its published sequence, producing the second synthetic genome, spanning two years.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In 2003, the 5386 bp genome of the bacteriophage Phi X 174 was assembled in about two weeks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Craig Venter Institute, constructed and patented a synthetic genome of a novel minimal bacterium, *Mycoplasma laboratorium* and were working on getting it functioning in a living cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In 2007, it was reported that several companies were offering synthesis of genetic sequences up to 2000 base pairs (bp) long, for a price of about $1 per bp and a turnaround time of less than two weeks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Oligonucleotides harvested from a photolithographic- or inkjet-manufactured DNA chip combined with PCR and DNA mismatch error-correction allows inexpensive large-scale changes of codons in genetic systems to improve gene expression or incorporate novel amino-acids *(see George M.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Church's and Anthony Forster's synthetic cell projects.)*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This favors a synthesis-from-scratch approach.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Additionally, the CRISPR/Cas system has emerged as a promising technique for gene editing.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It was described as "the most important innovation in the synthetic biology space in nearly 30 years".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] While other methods take months or years to edit gene sequences, CRISPR speeds that time up to weeks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Due to its ease of use and accessibility, however, it has raised ethical concerns, especially surrounding its use in biohacking.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] DNA sequencing determines the order of nucleotide bases in a DNA molecule.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biologists use DNA sequencing in their work in several ways.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] First, large-scale genome sequencing efforts continue to provide information on naturally occurring organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This information provides a rich substrate from which synthetic biologists can construct parts and devices.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Second, sequencing can verify that the fabricated system is as intended.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Third, fast, cheap, and reliable sequencing can facilitate rapid detection and identification of synthetic systems and organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] This is the ability of a system or component to operate without reference to its context.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The most used standardized DNA parts are BioBrick plasmids, invented by Tom Knight in 2003.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Biobricks are stored at the Registry of Standard Biological Parts in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The BioBrick standard has been used by tens of thousands of students worldwide in the international Genetically Engineered Machine (iGEM) competition.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] BioBrick Assembly Standard 10 promotes modularity by allowing BioBrick coding sequences to be spliced out and exchanged using restriction enzymes EcoRI or XbaI (BioBrick prefix) and SpeI and PstI (BioBrick suffix).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Sequence overlap between two genetic elements (genes or coding sequences), called overlapping genes, can prevent their individual manipulation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] To increase genome modularity, the practice of genome refactoring or improving "the internal structure of an existing system for future use, while simultaneously maintaining external system function" has been adopted across synthetic biology disciplines.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Some notable examples of refactoring including the nitrogen fixation cluster and type III secretion system along with bacteriophages T7 and ΦX174.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] While DNA is most important for information storage, a large fraction of the cell's activities are carried out by proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Tools can send proteins to specific regions of the cell and to link different proteins together.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] The interaction strength between protein partners should be tunable between a lifetime of seconds (desirable for dynamic signaling events) up to an irreversible interaction (desirable for device stability or resilient to harsh conditions).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Interactions such as coiled coils, SH3 domain-peptide binding or SpyTag/SpyCatcher offer such control.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In addition, it is necessary to regulate protein-protein interactions in cells, such as with light (using light-oxygen-voltage-sensing domains) or cell-permeable small molecules by chemically induced dimerization.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In a living cell, molecular motifs are embedded in a bigger network with upstream and downstream components.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] These components may alter the signaling capability of the modeling module.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] In the case of ultrasensitive modules, the sensitivity contribution of a module can differ from the sensitivity that the module sustains in isolation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Models inform the design of engineered biological systems by better predicting system behavior prior to fabrication.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Synthetic biology benefits from better models of how biological molecules bind substrates and catalyze reactions, how DNA encodes the information needed to specify the cell and how multi-component integrated systems behave.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Multiscale models of gene regulatory networks focus on synthetic biology applications.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Simulations can model all biomolecular interactions in transcription, translation, regulation and induction of gene regulatory networks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Only extensive modelling can enable the exploration of dynamic gene expression in a form suitable for research and design due to the numerous involved species and the intricacy of their relationships.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Dynamic simulations of the entire biomolecular interconnection involved in regulation, transport, transcription, induction, and translation enable the molecular level detailing of designs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] As opposed to modelling artificial networks a posteriori, this is contrasted.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Microfluidics, in particular droplet microfluidics, is an emerging tool used to construct new components, and to analyze and characterize them.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] It is widely employed in screening assays.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Studies have considered the components of the DNA transcription mechanism.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] One desire of scientists creating synthetic biological circuits is to be able to control the transcription of synthetic DNA in unicellular organisms (prokaryotes) and in multicellular organisms (eukaryotes).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] One study tested the adjustability of synthetic transcription factors (sTFs) in areas of transcription output and cooperative ability among multiple transcription factor complexes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] Researchers were able to mutate functional regions called zinc fingers, the DNA specific component of sTFs, to decrease their affinity for specific operator DNA sequence sites, and thus decrease the associated site-specific activity of the sTF (usually transcriptional regulation).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p01] They further used the zinc fingers as components of complex-forming sTFs, which are the eukaryotic translation mechanisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology initiatives frequently aim to redesign organisms so that they can create a material, such as a drug or fuel, or acquire a new function, such as the ability to sense something in the environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A biosensor refers to an engineered organism, usually a bacterium, that is capable of reporting some ambient phenomenon such as the presence of heavy metals or toxins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One such system is the Lux operon of *Aliivibrio fischeri,* which codes for the enzyme that is the source of bacterial bioluminescence, and can be placed after a respondent promoter to express the luminescence genes in response to a specific environmental stimulus.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One such sensor created, consisted of a bioluminescent bacterial coating on a photosensitive computer chip to detect certain petroleum pollutants.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] When the bacteria sense the pollutant, they luminesce.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Another example of a similar mechanism is the detection of landmines by an engineered *E.coli* reporter strain capable of detecting TNT and its main degradation product DNT, and consequently producing a green fluorescent protein (GFP).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Modified organisms can sense environmental signals and send output signals that can be detected and serve diagnostic purposes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Biosensors could also be used to detect pathogenic signatures—such as of SARS-CoV-2—and can be wearable.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] For the purpose of detecting and reacting to various and temporary environmental factors, cells have developed a wide range of regulatory circuits, ranging from transcriptional to post-translational.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] These circuits are made up of transducer modules that filter the signals and activate a biological response, as well as carefully designed sensitive sections that attach analytes and regulate signal-detection thresholds.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Modularity and selectivity are programmed to biosensor circuits at the transcriptional, translational, and post-translational levels, to achieve the delicate balancing of the two basic sensing modules.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This sector focuses primarily on the production of animal-derived products, including meat, milk,, honey, and eggs, obtained through cell culture.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] It is proposed as a sustainable alternative to livestock farming and slaughter, practices that pose significant global challenges in terms of environmental impact (e.g., of meat production), animal welfare, food security, and human health.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] However, not all synthetic nutrition products are animal food products – for instance, as of 2021, there are also products of synthetic coffee that are reported to be close to commercialization.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Photosynthetic microbial cells have been used as a step to synthetic production of spider silk.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A biological computer refers to an engineered biological system that can perform computer-like operations, which is a dominant paradigm in synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Researchers built and characterized a variety of logic gates in a number of organisms, and demonstrated both analog and digital computation in living cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] They demonstrated that bacteria can be engineered to perform both analog and/or digital computation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2007, in human cells, research demonstrated a universal logic evaluator that operates in mammalian cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Subsequently, researchers utilized this paradigm to demonstrate a proof-of-concept therapy that uses biological digital computation to detect and kill human cancer cells in 2011.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2016, another group of researchers demonstrated that principles of computer engineering can be used to automate digital circuit design in bacterial cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2017, researchers demonstrated the 'Boolean logic and arithmetic through DNA excision' (BLADE) system to engineer digital computation in human cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2019, researchers implemented a perceptron in biological systems opening the way for machine learning in these systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Cells use interacting genes and proteins, which are called gene circuits, to implement diverse function, such as responding to environmental signals, decision making and communication.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Three key components are involved: DNA, RNA and Synthetic biologist designed gene circuits that can control gene expression from several levels including transcriptional, post-transcriptional and translational levels.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Traditional metabolic engineering has been bolstered by the introduction of combinations of foreign genes and optimization by directed evolution.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This includes engineering *E. coli* and yeast for commercial production of a precursor of the antimalarial drug, Artemisinin.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Entire organisms have yet to be created from scratch, although living cells can be transformed with new DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Several ways allow constructing synthetic DNA components and even entire synthetic genomes, but once the desired genetic code is obtained, it is integrated into a living cell that is expected to manifest the desired new capabilities or phenotypes while growing and thriving.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Cell transformation is used to create biological circuits, which can be manipulated to yield desired outputs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] By integrating synthetic biology with materials science, it would be possible to use cells as microscopic molecular foundries to produce materials whose properties were genetically encoded.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Re-engineering has produced Curli fibers, the amyloid component of extracellular material of biofilms, as a platform for programmable nanomaterial.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] These nanofibers were genetically constructed for specific functions, including adhesion to substrates, nanoparticle templating and protein immobilization.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Natural proteins can be engineered, for example, by directed evolution, novel protein structures that match or improve on the functionality of existing proteins can be produced.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One group generated a helix bundle that was capable of binding oxygen with similar properties as hemoglobin, yet did not bind carbon monoxide.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A similar protein structure was generated to support a variety of oxidoreductase activities while another formed a structurally and sequentially novel ATPase.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Another group generated a family of G-protein coupled receptors that could be activated by the inert small molecule clozapine N-oxide but insensitive to the native ligand, acetylcholine; these receptors are known as DREADDs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Novel functionalities or protein specificity can also be engineered using computational approaches.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One study was able to use two different computational methods: a bioinformatics and molecular modeling method to mine sequence databases, and a computational enzyme design method to reprogram enzyme specificity.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Both methods resulted in designed enzymes with greater than 100 fold specificity for production of longer chain alcohols from sugar.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Another common investigation is expansion of the natural set of 20 amino acids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Excluding stop codons, 61 codons have been identified, but only 20 amino acids are coded generally in all organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Certain codons are engineered to code for alternative amino acids including: nonstandard amino acids such as O-methyl tyrosine; or exogenous amino acids such as 4-fluorophenylalanine.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Typically, these projects make use of re-coded nonsense suppressor tRNA-Aminoacyl tRNA synthetase pairs from other organisms, though in most cases substantial engineering is required.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Other researchers investigated protein structure and function by reducing the normal set of 20 amino acids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Limited protein sequence libraries are made by generating proteins where groups of amino acids may be replaced by a single amino acid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] For instance, several non-polar amino acids within a protein can all be replaced with a single non-polar amino acid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One project demonstrated that an engineered version of Chorismate mutase still had catalytic activity when only nine amino acids were used.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Researchers and companies practice synthetic biology to synthesize industrial enzymes with high activity, optimal yields and effectiveness.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] These synthesized enzymes aim to improve products such as detergents and lactose-free dairy products, as well as make them more cost effective.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The improvements of metabolic engineering by synthetic biology is an example of a biotechnological technique utilized in industry to discover pharmaceuticals and fermentive chemicals.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology may investigate modular pathway systems in biochemical production and increase yields of metabolic production.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Artificial enzymatic activity and subsequent effects on metabolic reaction rates and yields may develop "efficient new strategies for improving cellular properties ... for industrially important biochemical production".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Scientists can encode digital information onto a single strand of synthetic DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Church encoded one of his books about synthetic biology in DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The 5.3 Mb of data was more than 1000 times greater than the previous largest amount of information to be stored in synthesized DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A similar project encoded the complete sonnets of William Shakespeare in DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] More generally, algorithms such as NUPACK, ViennaRNA, Ribosome Binding Site Calculator, Cello, and Non-Repetitive Parts Calculator enables the design of new genetic systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Many technologies have been developed for incorporating unnatural nucleotides and amino acids into nucleic acids and proteins, both in vitro and in vivo.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] For example, in May 2014, researchers announced that they had successfully introduced two new artificial nucleotides into bacterial DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] By including individual artificial nucleotides in the culture media, they were able to exchange the bacteria 24 times; they did not generate mRNA or proteins able to use the artificial nucleotides.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology raised NASA's interest as it could help to produce resources for astronauts from a restricted portfolio of compounds sent from Earth.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] On Mars, in particular, synthetic biology could lead to production processes based on local resources, making it a powerful tool in the development of occupied outposts with less dependence on Earth.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Work has gone into developing plant strains that are able to cope with the harsh Martian environment, using similar techniques to those employed to increase resilience to certain environmental factors in agricultural crops.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One important topic in synthetic biology is *synthetic life*, that is concerned with hypothetical organisms created *in vitro* from biomolecules and/or chemical analogues thereof.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic life experiments attempt to either probe the origins of life, study some of the properties of life, or more ambitiously to recreate life from non-living (abiotic) components.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic life biology attempts to create living organisms capable of carrying out important functions, from manufacturing pharmaceuticals to detoxifying polluted land and water.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In medicine, it offers prospects of using designer biological parts as a starting point for new classes of therapies and diagnostic tools.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A living "artificial cell" has been defined as a completely synthetic cell that can capture energy, maintain ion gradients, contain macromolecules as well as store information and have the ability to mutate.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] It has been claimed that this would be difficult, although researcher have created contenders for such artificial cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A completely synthetic bacterial chromosome was produced in 2010 by Craig Venter, and his team introduced it to genomically emptied bacterial host cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The host cells were able to grow and replicate.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The *Mycoplasma laboratorium* is the only living organism with completely engineered genome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The first living organism with 'artificial' expanded DNA code was presented in 2014; the team used *E. coli* that had its genome extracted and replaced with a chromosome with an expanded genetic code.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The nucleosides added are d5SICS and dNaM.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2017, the international Build-a-Cell large-scale open-source research collaboration for the construction of synthetic living cells was started, followed by national synthetic cell organizations in several countries, including FabriCell, MaxSynBio and BaSyC.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The European synthetic cell efforts were unified in 2019 as SynCellEU initiative.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2023, researchers were able to create the first synthetically made human embryos derived from stem cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In therapeutics, synthetic biology has achieved significant advancements in altering and simplifying the therapeutics scope in a relatively short period of time.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In fact, new therapeutic platforms, from the discovery of disease mechanisms and drug targets to the manufacture and transport of small molecules, are made possible by the logical and model-guided design construction of biological components.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology devices have been designed to act as therapies in therapeutic treatment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] It is possible to control complete created viruses and organisms to target particular pathogens and diseased pathways.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Thus, in two independent studies 91,92, researchers utilised genetically modified bacteriophages to fight antibiotic-resistant bacteria by giving them genetic features that specifically target and hinder bacterial defences against antibiotic activity.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In the therapy of cancer, since conventional medicines frequently indiscriminately target tumours and normal tissues, artificially created viruses and organisms that can identify and connect their therapeutic action to pathological signals may be helpful.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] For example, p53 pathway activity in human cells was put into adenoviruses to control how they replicated.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Bacteria have long been used in cancer treatment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] *Bifidobacterium* and *Clostridium* selectively colonize tumors and reduce their size.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Recently synthetic biologists reprogrammed bacteria to sense and respond to a particular cancer state.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Most often bacteria are used to deliver a therapeutic molecule directly to the tumor to minimize off-target effects.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] To target the tumor cells, peptides that can specifically recognize a tumor were expressed on the surfaces of bacteria.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Peptides used include an affibody molecule that specifically targets human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 and a synthetic adhesin.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The other way is to allow bacteria to sense the tumor microenvironment, for example hypoxia, by building an AND logic gate into bacteria.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Then the bacteria only release target therapeutic molecules to the tumor through either lysis or the bacterial secretion system.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Lysis has the advantage that it can stimulate the immune system and control growth.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Multiple types of secretion systems can be used and other strategies as well.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The system is inducible by external signals.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Inducers include chemicals, electromagnetic or light waves.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Multiple species and strains are applied in these therapeutics.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Most commonly used bacteria are *Salmonella typhimurium*, *Escherichia coli*, *Bifidobacteria*, *Streptococcus*, *Lactobacillus*, *Listeria* and *Bacillus subtilis*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Each of these species have their own property and are unique to cancer therapy in terms of tissue colonization, interaction with immune system and ease of application.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biologists are developing genetically modified live yeast that can deliver therapeutic biologic medicines.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] When orally delivered, these live yeast act like micro-factories and will make therapeutic molecules directly in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Because yeast are eukaryotic, a key benefit is that they can be administered together with antibiotics.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Probiotic yeast expressing human P2Y2 purinergic receptor suppressed intestinal inflammation in mouse models of inflammatory bowel disease.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A live S. boulardii yeast delivering a tetra-specific anti-toxin that potently neutralizes Toxin A and Toxin B of *Clostridioides difficile* has been developed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This therapeutic anti-toxin is a fusion of four single-domain antibodies (nanobodies) that potently and broadly neutralize the two major virulence factors of C. difficile at the site of infection in preclinical models.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The first in human clinical trial of engineered live yeast for the treatment of Clostridioides difficile infection is anticipated in 2024 and will be sponsored by the developer Fzata, Inc.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The immune system plays an important role in cancer and can be harnessed to attack cancer cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Cell-based therapies focus on immunotherapies, mostly by engineering T cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] T cell receptors were engineered and 'trained' to detect cancer epitopes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Chimeric antigen receptors (CARs) are composed of a fragment of an antibody fused to intracellular T cell signaling domains that can activate and trigger proliferation of the cell.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Multiple second generation CAR-based therapies have been approved by FDA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Gene switches were designed to enhance safety of the treatment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Kill switches were developed to terminate the therapy should the patient show severe side effects.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Mechanisms can more finely control the system and stop and reactivate it.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Since the number of T-cells are important for therapy persistence and severity, growth of T-cells is also controlled to dial the effectiveness and safety of therapeutics.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Although several mechanisms can improve safety and control, limitations include the difficulty of inducing large DNA circuits into the cells and risks associated with introducing foreign components, especially proteins, into cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The most popular biofuel is ethanol produced from corn or sugar cane, but this method of producing biofuels is troublesome and constrained due to the high agricultural cost and inadequate fuel characteristics of ethanol.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A substitute and potential source of renewable energy is microbes that have had their metabolic pathways altered to be more efficient at converting biomass into biofuels.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Only if their production costs could be made to match or even beat those of present fuel production can these techniques be expected to be successful.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Related to this, there are several medicines whose pricey manufacturing procedures prevent them from having a larger therapeutic range.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The creation of new materials and the microbiological manufacturing of biomaterials would both benefit substantially from novel artificial biology tools.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The clustered frequently interspaced short palindromic repetitions (CRISPR)/CRISPR associated (Cas) system is a powerful method of genome engineering in a range of organisms because of its simplicity, modularity, and scalability.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In this technique, a guide RNA (gRNA) attracts the CRISPR nuclease Cas9 to a particular spot in the genome, causing a double strand break.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Several DNA repair processes, including homology-directed recombination and non-homology end joining, can be used to accomplish the desired genome change (i.e., gene deletion or insertion).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Additionally, dCas9 (dead Cas9 or nuclease-deficient Cas9), a Cas9 double mutant (H840A, D10A), has been utilised to control gene expression in bacteria or when linked to a stimulation of suppression site in yeast.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] To build and develop biological systems, regulating components including regulators, ribosome-binding sites (RBSs), and terminators are crucial.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Despite years of study, there are many various varieties and numbers of promoters and terminators for Escherichia coli, but also for the well-researched model organism Saccharomyces cerevisiae, as well as for other organisms of interest, these tools are quite scarce.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Numerous techniques have been invented for the finding and identification of promoters and terminators in order to overcome this constraint, including genome mining, random mutagenesis, hybrid engineering, biophysical modelling, combinatorial design, and rational design.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology has been used for organoids, which are lab-grown organs with application to medical research and transplantation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] 3D bioprinting can be used to reconstruct tissue from various regions of the body.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The precursor to the adoption of 3D printing in healthcare was a series of trials conducted by researchers at Boston Children's Hospital.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The team built replacement urinary bladders by hand for seven patients by constructing scaffolds, then layering the scaffolds with cells from the patients and allowing them to grow.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The trials were a success as the patients remained in good health 7 years after implantation, which led a research fellow named Anthony Atala, MD, to search for ways to automate the process.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Patients with end-stage bladder disease can now be treated by using bio-engineered bladder tissues to rebuild the damaged organ.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This technology can also potentially be applied to bone, skin, cartilage and muscle tissue.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Though one long-term goal of 3D bioprinting technology is to reconstruct an entire organ as well as minimize the problem of the lack of organs for transplantation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] There has been little success in bioprinting of fully functional organs e.g. liver, skin, meniscus or pancreas.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Unlike implantable stents, organs have complex shapes and are significantly harder to bioprint.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A bioprinted heart, for example, must not only meet structural requirements, but also vascularization, mechanical load, and electrical signal propagation requirements.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2022, the first success of a clinical trial for a 3D bioprinted transplant that is made from the patient's own cells, an external ear to treat microtia, was reported.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The limitations of 3D bioprinting are associated with physiologically irrelevant morphology and unsuccessful histological evaluation methods.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] 3D bioprinting contributes to significant advances in the medical field of tissue engineering by allowing for research to be done on innovative materials called biomaterials.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Some of the most notable bioengineered substances are usually stronger than the average bodily materials, including soft tissue and bone.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] These constituents can act as future substitutes, even improvements, for the original body materials.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In addition, the Defense Threat Reduction Agency aims to print mini organs such as hearts, livers, and lungs as the potential to test new drugs more accurately and perhaps eliminate the need for testing in animals.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] There is ongoing research and development into synthetic biology based methods for inducing regeneration in humans as well the creation of transplantable artificial organs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology can be used for creating nanoparticles which can be used for drug-delivery as well as for other purposes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Complementing research and development seeks to and has created synthetic cells that mimics functions of biological cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Applications include medicine such as designer-nanoparticles that make blood cells eat away—from the inside out—portions of atherosclerotic plaque that cause heart attacks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic micro-droplets for algal cells or synergistic algal-bacterial multicellular spheroid microbial reactors, for example, could be used to produce hydrogen as hydrogen economy biotechnology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Mammalian designer cells are engineered by humans to behave a specific way, such as an immune cell that expresses a synthetic receptor designed to combat a specific disease.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Electrogenetics is an application of synthetic biology that involves utilizing electrical fields to stimulate a response in engineered cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Controlling the designer cells can be done with relative ease through the use of common electronic devices, such as smartphones.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Additionally, electrogenetics allows for the possibility of creating devices that are much smaller and compact than devices that use other stimulus through the use of microscopic electrodes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One example of how electrogenetics is used to benefit public health is through stimulating designer cells that are able to produce/deliver therapeutics.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This was implemented in ElectroHEK cells, cells that contain voltage-gated calcium channels that are electrosensitive, meaning that the ion channel can be controlled by electrical conduction between electrodes and the ElectroHEK cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The expression levels of the artificial gene that these ElectroHEK cells contained was shown to be able to be controlled by changing the voltage or electrical pulse length.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Further studies have expanded on this robust system, one of which is a beta cell line system designed to control the release of insulin based on electric signals.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The creation of new life and the tampering of existing life has raised ethical concerns in the field of synthetic biology and are actively being discussed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The ethical aspects of synthetic biology has three main features: biosafety, biosecurity, and the creation of new life forms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Other ethical issues mentioned include the regulation of new creations, patent management of new creations, benefit distribution, and research integrity.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Ethical issues have surfaced for recombinant DNA and genetically modified organism (GMO) technologies and extensive regulations of genetic engineering and pathogen research were in place in many jurisdictions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Amy Gutmann, former head of the Presidential Bioethics Commission, argued that we should avoid the temptation to over-regulate synthetic biology in general, and genetic engineering in particular.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] According to Gutmann, "Regulatory parsimony is especially important in emerging technologies...where the temptation to stifle innovation on the basis of uncertainty and fear of the unknown is particularly great.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The blunt instruments of statutory and regulatory restraint may not only inhibit the distribution of new benefits, but can be counterproductive to security and safety by preventing researchers from developing effective safeguards.".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] One ethical question is whether or not it is acceptable to create new life forms, sometimes known as "playing God".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Currently, the creation of new life forms not present in nature is at small-scale, the potential benefits and dangers remain unknown, and careful consideration and oversight are ensured for most studies.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Many advocates express the great potential value—to agriculture, medicine, and academic knowledge, among other fields—of creating artificial life forms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Creation of new entities could expand scientific knowledge well beyond what is currently known from studying natural phenomena.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Yet there is concern that artificial life forms may reduce nature's "purity" (i.e., nature could be somehow corrupted by human intervention and manipulation) and potentially influence the adoption of more engineering-like principles instead of biodiversity- and nature-focused ideals.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Some are also concerned that if an artificial life form were to be released into nature, it could hamper biodiversity by beating out natural species for resources (similar to how algal blooms kill marine species).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Another concern involves the ethical treatment of newly created entities if they happen to sense pain, sentience, and self-perception.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] There is an ongoing debate as to whether such life forms should be granted moral or legal rights, though no consensus exists as to how these rights would be administered or enforced.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] What is most ethically appropriate when considering biosafety measures?
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] How can accidental introduction of synthetic life in the natural environment be avoided?
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Much ethical consideration and critical thought has been given to these questions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Biosafety not only refers to biological containment; it also refers to strides taken to protect the public from potentially hazardous biological agents.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Even though such concerns are important and remain unanswered, not all products of synthetic biology present concern for biological safety or negative consequences for the environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] It is argued that most synthetic technologies are benign and are incapable of flourishing in the outside world due to their "unnatural" characteristics as there is yet to be an example of a transgenic microbe conferred with a fitness advantage in the wild.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In general, existing hazard controls, risk assessment methodologies, and regulations developed for traditional genetically modified organisms (GMOs) are considered to be sufficient for synthetic organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] "Extrinsic" biocontainment methods in a laboratory context include physical containment through biosafety cabinets and gloveboxes, as well as personal protective equipment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In an agricultural context, they include isolation distances and pollen barriers, similar to methods for biocontainment of GMOs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic organisms may offer increased hazard control because they can be engineered with "intrinsic" biocontainment methods that limit their growth in an uncontained environment, or prevent horizontal gene transfer to natural organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Some ethical issues relate to biosecurity, where biosynthetic technologies could be deliberately used to cause harm to society and/or the environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Since synthetic biology raises ethical issues and biosecurity issues, humanity must consider and plan on how to deal with potentially harmful creations, and what kinds of ethical measures could possibly be employed to deter nefarious biosynthetic technologies.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Additionally, the development of synthetic biology tools has made it easier for individuals with less education, training, and access to equipment to modify and use pathogenic organisms as bioweapons.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This increases the threat of bioterrorism, especially as terrorist groups become aware of the significant social, economic, and political disruption caused by pandemics like COVID-19.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] As new techniques are developed in the field of synthetic biology, the risk of bioterrorism is likely to continue to grow.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The European Union-funded project SYNBIOSAFE has issued reports on how to manage synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A 2007 paper identified key issues in safety, security, ethics, and the science-society interface, which the project defined as public education and ongoing dialogue among scientists, businesses, government and ethicists.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The key security issues that SYNBIOSAFE identified involved engaging companies that sell synthetic DNA and the biohacking community of amateur biologists.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Key ethical issues concerned the creation of new life forms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] A subsequent report focused on biosecurity, especially the so-called dual-use challenge.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] For example, while synthetic biology may lead to more efficient production of medical treatments, it may also lead to synthesis or modification of harmful pathogens (e.g., smallpox).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The biohacking community remains a source of special concern, as the distributed and diffuse nature of open-source biotechnology makes it difficult to track, regulate or mitigate potential concerns over biosafety and biosecurity.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] COSY, another European initiative, focuses on public perception and communication.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] To better communicate synthetic biology and its societal ramifications to a broader public, COSY and SYNBIOSAFE published *SYNBIOSAFE*, a 38-minute documentary film, in October 2009.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The International Association Synthetic Biology has proposed self-regulation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This proposes specific measures that the synthetic biology industry, especially DNA synthesis companies, should implement.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] In 2007, a group led by scientists from leading DNA-synthesis companies published a "practical plan for developing an effective oversight framework for the DNA-synthesis industry".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Sloan Foundation funded the Woodrow Wilson Center, the Hastings Center, and the J.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Craig Venter Institute to examine the public perception, ethics and policy implications of synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] On July 9–10, 2009, the National Academies' Committee of Science, Technology & Law convened a symposium on "Opportunities and Challenges in the Emerging Field of Synthetic Biology".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] After the publication of the first synthetic genome and the accompanying media coverage about "life" being created, President Barack Obama established the Presidential Commission for the Study of Bioethical Issues to study synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] It noted that synthetic biology is an emerging field, which creates potential risks and rewards.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The commission did not recommend policy or oversight changes and called for continued funding of the research and new funding for monitoring, study of emerging ethical issues and public education.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology, as a major tool for biological advances, results in the "potential for developing biological weapons, possible unforeseen negative impacts on human health ... and any potential environmental impact".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The proliferation of such technology could also make the production of biological and chemical weapons available to a wider array of state and non-state actors.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] These security issues may be avoided by regulating industry uses of biotechnology through policy legislation.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] On March 13, 2012, over 100 environmental and civil society groups, including Friends of the Earth, the International Center for Technology Assessment, and the ETC Group, issued the manifesto *The Principles for the Oversight of Synthetic Biology*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] This manifesto calls for a worldwide moratorium on the release and commercial use of synthetic organisms until more robust regulations and rigorous biosafety measures are established.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The groups specifically call for an outright ban on the use of synthetic biology on the human genome or human microbiome.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The hazards of synthetic biology include biosafety hazards to workers and the public, biosecurity hazards stemming from deliberate engineering of organisms to cause harm, and environmental hazards.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] The biosafety hazards are similar to those for existing fields of biotechnology, mainly exposure to pathogens and toxic chemicals, although novel synthetic organisms may have novel risks.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] For biosecurity, there is concern that synthetic or redesigned organisms could theoretically be used for bioterrorism.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Potential risks include recreating known pathogens from scratch, engineering existing pathogens to be more dangerous, and engineering microbes to produce harmful biochemicals.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Lastly, environmental hazards include adverse effects on biodiversity and ecosystem services, including potential changes to land use resulting from agricultural use of synthetic organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology is an example of a dual-use technology with the potential to be used in ways that could intentionally or unintentionally harm humans and/or damage the environment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Often "scientists, their host institutions and funding bodies" consider whether the planned research could be misused and sometimes implement measures to reduce the likelihood of misuse.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Existing risk analysis systems for GMOs are generally considered sufficient for synthetic organisms, although there may be difficulties for an organism built "bottom-up" from individual genetic sequences.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/synthetic-biology-p02] Synthetic biology generally falls under existing regulations for GMOs and biotechnology in general, and any regulations that exist for downstream commercial products, although there are generally no regulations in any jurisdiction that are specific to synthetic biology.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] "Astro" means "star" and "exo" means "outside".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Both exo- and astrobiology deal with the search for naturally evolved life in the Universe, mostly on other planets in the circumstellar habitable zone.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] (These are also occasionally referred to as xenobiology.) Whereas astrobiologists are concerned with the detection and analysis of life elsewhere in the Universe, xenobiology attempts to design forms of life with a different biochemistry or different genetic code than on planet Earth.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In xenobiology, the aim is to design and construct biological systems that differ from their natural counterparts on one or more fundamental levels.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Ideally these new-to-nature organisms would be different in every possible biochemical aspect exhibiting a very different genetic code.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] The long-term goal is to construct a cell that would store its genetic information not in DNA but in an alternative informational polymer consisting of xeno nucleic acids (XNA), different base pairs, using non-canonical amino acids and an altered genetic code.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] So far cells have been constructed that incorporate only one or two of these features.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Originally this research on alternative forms of DNA was driven by the question of how life evolved on earth and why RNA and DNA were selected by (chemical) evolution over other possible nucleic acid structures.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Two hypotheses for the selection of RNA and DNA as life's backbone are either they are favored under life on Earth's conditions, or they were coincidentally present in pre-life chemistry and continue to be used now.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Systematic experimental studies aiming at the diversification of the chemical structure of nucleic acids have resulted in completely novel informational biopolymers.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] So far a number of XNAs with new chemical backbones or leaving group of the DNA have been synthesized, e.g.: hexose nucleic acid (HNA); threose nucleic acid (TNA), glycol nucleic acid (GNA) cyclohexenyl nucleic acid (CeNA).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] The incorporation of XNA in a plasmid, involving 3 HNA codons, has been accomplished already in 2003.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] This XNA is used in vivo (E coli) as template for DNA synthesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] This study, using a binary (G/T) genetic cassette and two non-DNA bases (Hx/U), was extended to CeNA, while GNA seems to be too alien at this moment for the natural biological system to be used as template for DNA synthesis.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Extended bases using a natural DNA backbone could, likewise, be transliterated into natural DNA, although to a more limited extent.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Aside being used as extensions to template DNA strands, XNA activity has been tested for use as genetic catalysts.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Although proteins are the most common components of cellular enzymatic activity, nucleic acids are also used in the cell to catalyze reactions.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] A 2015 study found several different kinds of XNA, most notably FANA (2'-fluoroarabino nucleic acids), as well as HNA, CeNA and ANA (arabino nucleic acids) could be used to cleave RNA during post-transcriptional RNA processing acting as XNA enzymes, hence the name XNAzymes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] FANA XNAzymes also showed the ability to ligate DNA, RNA and XNA substrates.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Although XNAzyme studies are still preliminary, this study was a step in the direction of searching for synthetic circuit components that are more efficient than those containing DNA and RNA counterparts that can regulate DNA, RNA, and their own, XNA, substrates.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] While XNAs have modified backbones, other experiments target the replacement or enlargement of the genetic alphabet of DNA with unnatural base pairs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In a systematic study, Leconte et al. tested the viability of 60 candidate bases (yielding potentially 3600 base pairs) for possible incorporation in the DNA.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In 2002, Hirao et al. developed an unnatural base pair between 2-amino-8-(2-thienyl)purine (s) and pyridine-2-one (y) that functions *in vitro* in transcription and translation toward a genetic code for protein synthesis containing a non-standard amino acid.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In 2006, they created 7-(2-thienyl)imidazo[4,5-b]pyridine (Ds) and pyrrole-2-carbaldehyde (Pa) as a third base pair for replication and transcription, and afterward, Ds and 4-[3-(6-aminohexanamido)-1-propynyl]-2-nitropyrrole (Px) was discovered as a high fidelity pair in PCR amplification.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In 2013, they applied the Ds-Px pair to DNA aptamer generation by *in vitro* selection (SELEX) and demonstrated the genetic alphabet expansion significantly augment DNA aptamer affinities to target proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Neither the XNA nor the unnatural bases are recognized by natural polymerases.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] One of the major challenges is to find or create novel types of polymerases that will be able to replicate these new-to-nature constructs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In one case a modified variant of the HIV-reverse transcriptase was found to be able to PCR-amplify an oligonucleotide containing a third type base pair.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] (2012) demonstrated that the method of polymerase evolution and design successfully led to the storage and recovery of genetic information (of less than 100bp length) from six alternative genetic polymers based on simple nucleic acid architectures not found in nature, xeno nucleic acids.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] One of the goals of xenobiology is to rewrite the genetic code.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] The most promising approach to change the code is the reassignment of seldom used or even unused codons.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In an ideal scenario, the genetic code is expanded by one codon, thus having been liberated from its old function and fully reassigned to a non-canonical amino acid (ncAA) ("code expansion").
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In that situation, the canonical amino acid residues in native proteins are substituted with the ncAAs.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Even the insertion of multiple different ncAAs into the same protein is possible.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Finally, the repertoire of 20 canonical amino acids can not only be expanded, but also reduced to 19.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] By reassigning transfer RNA (tRNA)/aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase pairs the codon specificity can be changed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Cells endowed with such aminoacyl-[tRNA synthetases] are thus able to read [mRNA] sequences that make no sense to the existing gene expression machinery.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Altering the codon: tRNA synthetases pairs may lead to the in vivo incorporation of the non-canonical amino acids into proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In the past reassigning codons was mainly done on a limited scale.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Following the success of this genome wide codon replacement, the authors continued and achieved the reprogramming of 13 codons throughout the genome, directly affecting 42 essential genes.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] An even more radical change in the genetic code is the change of a triplet codon to a quadruplet and even quintuplet codon pioneered by Sisido in cell-free systems and by Schultz in bacteria.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Finally, non-natural base pairs can be used to introduce novel amino acid in proteins.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] The goal of substituting DNA by XNA may also be reached by another route, namely by engineering the environment instead of the genetic modules.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] This approach has been successfully demonstrated by Marlière and Mutzel with the production of an *E. coli* strain whose DNA is composed of standard A, C and G nucleotides but has the synthetic thymine analogue 5-chlorouracil instead of thymine (T) in the corresponding positions of the sequence.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] These cells are then dependent on externally supplied 5-chlorouracil for growth, but otherwise they look and behave as normal *E. coli*.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] These cells, however, are currently not yet fully auxotrophic for the Xeno-base since they are still growing on thymine when this is supplied to the medium.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Xenobiological systems are designed to convey orthogonality to natural biological systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] A (still hypothetical) organism that uses XNA, different base pairs and polymerases and has an altered genetic code will hardly be able to interact with natural forms of life on the genetic level.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Thus, these xenobiological organisms represent a genetic enclave that cannot exchange information with natural cells.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Altering the genetic machinery of the cell leads to semantic containment.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In analogy to information processing in IT, this safety concept is termed a "genetic firewall".
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] The concept of the genetic firewall seems to overcome a number of limitations of previous safety systems.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] A first experimental evidence of the theoretical concept of the genetic firewall was achieved in 2013 with the construction of a genomically recoded organism (GRO).
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] In this GRO all known UAG stop codons in E.coli were replaced by UAA codons, which allowed for the deletion of release factor 1 and reassignment of UAG translation function.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] The GRO exhibited increased resistance to T7 bacteriophage, thus showing that alternative genetic codes do reduce genetic compatibility.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] This GRO, however, is still very similar to its natural "parent" and cannot be regarded to have a genetic firewall.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] The possibility of reassigning the function of large number of triplets opens the perspective to have strains that combine XNA, novel base pairs, new genetic codes, etc. that cannot exchange any information with the natural biological world.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Regardless of changes leading to a semantic containment mechanism in new organisms, any novel biochemical systems still has to undergo a toxicological screening.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] XNA, novel proteins, etc. might represent novel toxins, or have an allergic potential that needs to be assessed.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Xenobiology might challenge the regulatory framework, as currently laws and directives deal with genetically modified organisms and do not directly mention chemically or genomically modified organisms.
[src:synthetic-biology-deep/xenobiology] Taking into account that real xenobiology organisms are not expected in the next few years, policy makers do have some time at hand to prepare themselves for an upcoming governance challenge.
